rs related to working and living conditions have proved themselves to be precarious. The author introduces the most important economic and sociological theories of precarization, and demonstrates that precarity has seized society in its entirety. We live in the society of precarity. But what can be drawn from this? Marchart describes contemporary social protests and their demands. He investigates their democratic and political implications and works towards a social theory of the conflict and of its contingencies.  afunded by OAPEN-CH-SNF  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aDemokratie. 4aDiskurs. 4aExklusion. 4aGesellschaft. 4aMedien. 4aPolitik. 4aProtest. 4aSoziale Bewegungen. 4aSoziale Ungleichheit. 4aSoziologie. 4aSoziologische Theorie. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh  aDemocracy.  aMedia.  aPolitics.  aSocial Inequality.  aSociety.  aSociological Theory.  aSociology.2 aOAPEN-CH-SNFefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript: Complete eBook-Package 2013z9783110401219oZDB-23-TGP0 cprintz978383762192140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/transcript.9783839421925?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839421925zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783839421925/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA  aZDB-23-TGPb2013